Therefore, the best angular resolution is 3.4e-6 radians. **Final Answer** The best angular resolution is \boxed{3.4 \times 10^{-6}} radians. </think> To determine the best angular resolution of the radio image produced by the Very Large Array (VLA) at a wavelength of 10 cm with a maximum baseline of 36 km, we use the formula for angular resolution in interferometry: \[ \theta = 1.22 \frac{\lambda}{B} \] where: - \(\theta\) is the angular resolution in radians, - \(\lambda\) is the wavelength (10 cm), - \(B\) is the baseline length (36 km). First, convert the wavelength and baseline to consistent units. The wavelength is already in centimeters, and the baseline needs to be converted to centimeters: - 36 km = 36,000 meters = 3,600,000 cm. Substitute the values into the formula: \[ \theta = 1.22 \frac{10 \text{ cm}}{3,600,000 \text{ cm}} \] Calculate the ratio: \[ \frac{10 \text{ cm}}{3,600,000 \text{ cm}} = \frac{10}{3,600,000} = \frac{1}{360,000} \approx 2.7778 \times 10^{-6} \] Multiply by 1.22: \[ \theta = 1.22 \times 2.7778 \times 10^{-6} \approx 3.3889 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \] Considering the significant figures (the given values have two significant figures), we round the result to two significant figures: \[ \theta \approx 3.4 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \] Thus, the best angular resolution of the radio image is \(\boxed{3.4 \times 10^{-6}}\) radians.
